Safety is not a feature. It is something that either pervades a product or it doesn't — and users know, within seconds, whether it does.

> Safety, in our experience, feels like being allowed to be messy. Not being cleaned up.

## The design of non-judgment

Non-judgment is harder to design than it sounds. It is not just the absence of negative responses.

![Every interaction is a micro-decision about whether someone feels safe to continue.](https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1573496359142-b8d87734a5a2?w=1200&q=80)

## Privacy as foundation

Structural safety matters as much as tonal safety. Our early non-negotiable decisions:

- No advertising — ever
- No selling of user data — ever
- End-to-end encryption for all session content
- No identifying information linked to session data

## The ongoing work

We review safety failures every week — moments where a user felt dismissed, managed, or talked at instead of heard.
